140. slots ⭐
slots is a special class-level attribute which reduces memory consumption by preventing the creation of instance dictionaries and restricting allowed attributes.

Standard Class (Uses __dict__)python
class Player:
    def __init__(self, name, level):
        self.name = name
        self.level = level

p = Player("Alice", 10)
p.score = 100  # Works! You can add arbitrary attributes at runtime.
print(p.__dict__)  
# Output: {'name': 'Alice', 'level': 10, 'score': 100}

Use code with caution.Slotted Class (Uses __slots__)pythonclass SlottedPlayer:
    __slots__ = ("name", "level")  # Accepts a tuple or list of strings

    def __init__(self, name, level):
        self.name = name
        self.level = level


p = SlottedPlayer("Bob", 20)
# p.score = 100  # Raises AttributeError! Cannot add new attributes.
# print(p.__dict__)  # Raises AttributeError! __dict__ does not exist.



141. Globals and Locals
In programming, Globals and Locals refer to the "scope" or region of code where a variable is accessible.
Locals: Variables declared inside a specific function or block. They are only accessible within that block and are destroyed when it finishes.
Globals: Variables declared outside of any function. They can be accessed or modified from anywhere in your entire program

